        {
            "id": "6419e642bc07410b98c46",
            "questionText": "A seesaw consists of a uniform plank of length $!$L = 4\\,\\text{m}$!$ and mass $!$M = 10\\,\\text{kg}$!$, pivoted at its center. A child of mass $!$m_1 = 30\\,\\text{kg}$!$ sits at one end, and another child of mass $!$m_2 = 20\\,\\text{kg}$!$ sits $!$d = 1\\,\\text{m}$!$ from the other end. If the seesaw is released from rest in this unbalanced configuration, what is its initial angular acceleration?",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "19457b939be84a3c9dc7c",
                    "stepText": "Let's begin by identifying the concept that tells us how to calculate the rotational effect produced by a force. Which of the following formulas defines the torque ($!$\\tau$!$) produced by a force applied at a distance from a pivot?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "66c394e5-9b27-4235-9105-6b2e0ba0b2b0"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\tau = Fd$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\tau = F + d$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\tau = \\frac{F}{d}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "80503763c4d742ce841e3",
                    "stepText": "Great, now use the determined concept to compute the net torque about the seesaw's pivot. Consider the distances from the center: the first child is at $!$2\\,\\text{m}$!$ from the pivot, and the second child\u2019s distance from the pivot is $!$1\\,\\text{m}$!$. Using $!$g = 9.8\\,\\text{m/s}^2$!$, calculate the net torque by summing each child's contribution (taking proper sign conventions). What is the net torque (in $!$\\text{N}\\cdot\\text{m}$!$)?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "-392"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "N\u00b7m",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "66c394e5-9b27-4235-9105-6b2e0ba0b2b0"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "5016f80360db4423aa8ea",
                    "stepText": "Now, let\u2019s focus on the moment of inertia. For the uniform plank used as a seesaw, we need to recall the formula for the moment of inertia of a rod pivoted about its center. Which of the following formulas correctly represents this?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "e7c0b9dd-4995-4142-ba78-a54339d150c3"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$I = \\frac{1}{12} ML^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$I = \\frac{1}{2} ML^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$I = ML^2$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "5cd434a9dc814662a96f8",
                    "stepText": "Excellent. Now, calculate the total moment of inertia ($!$I_{total}$!$) of the seesaw system. First, compute the plank's moment of inertia using the rod formula. Then, add the contributions of the two children treated as point masses (using $!$m \\times r^2$!$ for each, where $!$r$!$ is the distance from the pivot). What is the total moment of inertia (in $!$\\text{kg}\\cdot\\text{m}^2$!$)?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "153.3"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "kg\u00b7m\u00b2",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "e7c0b9dd-4995-4142-ba78-a54339d150c3"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "4a84ed8ab0a247798c7a4",
                    "stepText": "Now that we have both the net torque and the total moment of inertia, let's identify the rotational dynamics relation that connects these quantities to angular acceleration ($!$\\alpha$!$). Which of the following formulas correctly relates them?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "3b2a38ec-ad3c-4fda-9fed-c1f652dea80e"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\alpha = \\frac{\\tau}{I}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\alpha = \\tau \\times I$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\alpha = \\frac{I}{\\tau}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "dbbcd2c12e574e658e24e",
                    "stepText": "Finally, use the net torque and the moment of inertia computed earlier to calculate the initial angular acceleration ($!$\\alpha$!$) of the seesaw. Divide the net torque by the total moment of inertia. What is the angular acceleration (in $!$\\text{rad/s}^2$!$)?",
